# Main Prompt

## Feature

- Main page wiht Chart: Chart that shows the net wealth from current age to death age.
- the chart should be interactive, allowing users to hover over points to see details.
- the chart should be generated based on user input data.
- the chart should be visually appealing and easy to understand.
- the chart should be updated dynamically as the user inputs new data.

- Financial Plan: User can input their assets, salary, and expenses to generate a financial plan
- user input is to be stored in browser local storage.

- Login and Register: User can register and login to the application.
- Login with email and password. 
- Registration should include email, password, and confirmation password.
- User Authentication: Implement secure user authentication using JWT tokens.

- Settings: User can update their profile and settings.
- Logout: User can log out of the application.

- Database will be SQL server. 
- Use EF Code first for database migrations and management.

- Responsive Design: Ensure the application is responsive and works on various devices.

- Backend should use Swagger

- Front should use Tailwind CSS for styling.

## Frontend

- logic change should be test by unit test.

## app build plan

1. Project Setup
Initialize a monorepo or two separate projects:
Frontend: Vue 3 + TypeScript
Backend: ASP.NET Core + C#
Set up ESLint and Prettier for the frontend.
Set up basic RESTful API structure in the backend.
2. Authentication (Login & Register)
Backend:
Implement user registration and login endpoints.
Use JWT for secure authentication.
Store user credentials securely (hash passwords).
Frontend:
Create registration and login forms (email, password, confirm password).
Store JWT token in browser (securely, e.g., HttpOnly cookie or localStorage).
Implement logout functionality.
3. User Profile & Settings
Backend:
Endpoints to get/update user profile and settings.
Frontend:
Profile/settings page for updating user info.
Allow user to log out.
4. Financial Plan Input
Frontend:
Form for users to input assets, salary, and expenses.
Store input in browser local storage.
Backend:
Endpoints to receive and process financial data (optional, if you want to persist on server).
5. Financial Plan Calculation
Backend:
Implement financial planning algorithms (project net wealth from current age to death age).
Return summary and yearly data.
Frontend:
Fetch calculated plan from backend (or calculate locally if preferred).
Display summary of the plan.
6. Interactive Chart
Frontend:
Use a modern charting library (e.g., Chart.js, ECharts, or ApexCharts for Vue 3).
Display net wealth over time.
Make chart interactive (hover for details, update dynamically as user changes input).
Ensure chart is visually appealing and easy to understand.
7. Responsive Design
Use CSS frameworks (e.g., Tailwind CSS, BootstrapVue) or custom CSS to ensure the app works on all devices.
8. Error Handling & Logging
Backend:
Implement proper error handling and logging.
Frontend:
Show user-friendly error messages.
9. Testing & Code Quality
Write unit and integration tests for both frontend and backend.
Use linters and formatters to maintain code quality.
10. Deployment
Prepare production builds for both frontend and backend.
Deploy to cloud or hosting provider (e.g., Azure, AWS, Vercel).
